{"key":"processedPost-9519916","value":{"id":9519916,"first":9519421,"last":9520914,"when":1230688376,"utime":"12/31/08 03:52 AM","content":"It all depends on what you're wanting to see.&nbsp; I use my stereo microscope far more often than my compound microscope.&nbsp; Are you wanting to examine mycelium to see if it's mono or dikaryotic?&nbsp; If so, you want a good compound microscope.&nbsp; If you're wanting to examine gills and or ID molds, a good stereo microscope is what you want.&nbsp; A stereo microscope is like a giant magnifying glass.&nbsp; It looks at reflected light.&nbsp; A compound microscope has the light below the specimen, so you see the light that shines through the object.<br />RR","title":"Re: So I'm looking for a good microscope","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}